An overview of 3cixty Developer APIs is provided here.

**Getting Started:**

 - To get started depending on your needs you either need `3cixty App Key` or `3cixty access_token` or `Google access_token` or `Facebook access_token`. The only APIs where above mentioned parameters are not required are `/validate` (validate sparql query conformity with sparql 1.1) and `/getScope` (know scopes in 3cixty API).
 - To get the `3cixty App Key` please use the [link](appchallenge) alternatviely you can also use the `/getAppKey` API below. In such a case you will need your google access token please open [https://api.3cixty.com/v2/googleToken.jsp](https://api.3cixty.com/v2/googleToken.jsp) on your web browser to get your `Google access_token`.
 - Once you have the `3cixty App key` please use the API as need. Note that some APIs use `3cixty access_token` while some need `Google access_token`. To get your `3cixty access_token` from `Google access_token` use the `/getAccessToken` API.


 Below are the Java code steps to be performed to successfully call the API you need

 - **Step 1**: use following code and specify the `<API>` parameter.

   <pre class="brush: java">URL url = new URL("https:\\api.3cixty.com\v2\&lt;API&gt;"));
   </pre>

 - **Step 2**: create the url connection as below. Here `<TYPE>` is either `GET` or `POST`

   <pre class="brush: java">URLConnection urlConn = url.openConnection();
   ((HttpURLConnection) urlConn).setRequestMethod("&ltTYPE&gt");
   </pre>

 - **Step 3**: Based on what parameters are required by the `<API>`, you need to either set the following:

   - for header paramaters
     <pre class="brush: java">con.setRequestProperty("access_token", &lt;ThreeCixtyAccessToken&gt;);
     //similary set other header parameters
     ...
     </pre>

   - for query parameters in the **Step 1**  provide the paramters in the `URL` itself. For example:
     <pre class="brush: java">URL url = new URL("https:\\api.3cixty.com\v2\&lt;API&gt;?
     google_access_token="&lt;googleAccessToken&gt;" + 
     "&amp;appid=" + &lt;appid&gt; +
     "&amp;appname=" + URLEncoder.encode(&lt;appname&gt;, "UTF-8") +
     "&amp;category=" + URLEncoder.encode(&lt;cat&gt;, "UTF-8")+
     "&amp;scopeName=" + URLEncoder.encode(&lt;scope&gt;, "UTF-8") + 
     "&amp;description=" + URLEncoder.encode(&lt;desc&gt;, "UTF-8") +
     "&amp;redirect_uri=" + URLEncoder.encode(&lt;redirect_uri&gt;, "UTF-8") + 
     "&amp;thumbNailUrl=" + URLEncoder.encode(&lt;thumbNailUrl&gt;, "UTF-8"))"));
     </pre>

   - for `JSON` input in the body use:

     <pre class="brush: java">String jsonString="&lt;json&gt;";
     </pre>

 - **Step 4**: Depending on the above step, 

   - for `JSON` as the input, use: 
     <pre class="brush: java">OutputStreamWriter writer = new OutputStreamWriter(urlConn.getOutputStream());
     writer.write(jsonString.getBytes(UTF8));
     </pre>

   - for other case, use:
     <pre class="brush: java">InputStream input = urlConn.getInputStream();
     StringBuffer buffer = new StringBuffer();
     byte[] b = new byte[1024];
     int readBytes = 0;
     while (true) { 
       readBytes = input.read(b);
       if (readBytes &lt; 0) break;
       buffer.append(new String(b, 0, readBytes));
     }
     input.close();
     JSONObject json = new JSONObject(buffer.toString());
     ...
     </pre>

